The article discusses the American Bar Association's (ABA) role in vetting judicial nominees for the White House. It criticizes the ABA for its perceived lack of political neutrality and argues that the Senate should remove the ABA from the vetting process. The article highlights the ABA's recent decision to deem Brett Talley "not qualified" to serve as a federal judge, despite previous instances where younger nominees were deemed qualified. It also mentions the ABA's history of political activism and questions the usefulness of their ratings. The article concludes by suggesting that if Republicans want Trump's judicial nominees to be confirmed, they should disregard the ABA's opinions.